recommandationVideos.Description:

recommandationVideos.Title: Ukraine calls for investigation after deadly plane crash in Russia | BBC News
recommandationVideos.Description:
Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky has accused Moscow of "playing with the lives of Ukrainian prisoners", after a deadly plane crash in western Russia.
 
He demanded an international inquiry after Wednesday's crash in the Belgorod region near Ukraine's border.
 
Russia said there were no survivors after Kyiv had downed the Il-76 plane with 65 Ukrainian prisoners of war, six Russian crew and three escorts.
 
Moscow claimed the Ukrainians were being flown for a prisoner exchange.
 
Ukraine's military intelligence (GUR) said it had not been told to ensure safe airspace, as on previous occasions.

recommandationVideos.Title: 'President Putin has made mistakes', Russia anti-war candidate says I BBC News
recommandationVideos.Description:
Russian opposition politician Boris Nadezhdin has said he has more than 100,000 signatures to register for the countryâ€™s upcoming presidential election.
 
President Vladimir Putin "has made lots of mistakes", he told the BBC, "not only the special military operation, he destroyed the constitution of Russia".
 
Photos on social media have shown people queuing to give their signatures and several opposition figures have voiced their backing for Nadezhdin, though many doubt he will ultimately be allowed to run.
 
Putin has said he would stand again for a fifth term in office. His re-election is seen as inevitable, with opposition almost non-existent and Russian media completely under his control.

recommandationVideos.Title: Is the West leaving Ukraine out to dry? | To the point
recommandationVideos.Description:
For NATO, a worst-case scenario would be a Russian attack on one of its member states. Now itâ€™s rehearsing for exactly that possibility: running its biggest military drills since the Cold War to practice its response.

The exercise, called Steadfast Defender, sees some 90,000 troops from 32 countries taking part with fighter jets, tanks, and warships: all shortly before the second anniversary of Russiaâ€™s full-scale invasion of Ukraine. Since then, Kyiv has fought to expel its invaders with help from Western weapon deliveries: but will the support continue? Today on To The Point weâ€™re looking at Putinâ€™s imperial ambitions, asking: Is the West leaving Ukraine out to dry?

The strikes on Russian facilities in Leningrad Region show that the Ukrainian army has effective long-range weapons, a Ukrainiani military expert and development director of the information and consulting company Defence Express, Valeriy Ryabykh, has said.
According to him, this indicates a transition to a new stage of combat operations. "The distance to the target in a straight line is 700 to 900 kilometres. In order to bypass the nodes of the Russian air defence and various threatening directions, then such a trajectory should be somewhere around 1,200 kilometres," the expert said on the air of "Espresso".
Ryabykh notes that these long-range weapons can bypass Russian air defence systems and hit facilities that the occupiers use to supply their army with fuel and lubricants and conduct economic activities.
"Russians who adore Putin can already observe the result of his policies directly from their windows, and far from the front line," he said.
Recently, Ukrainian presidential adviser Mykhailo Podolyak has called on Kyiv's allies to provide more weapons to aid the defense against Russiaâ€™s invasion.
According to Podolyak, the number of weapons should be large, since the entire front line is 1,300 kilometers long, and the fighting is taking place over 600 to 800 kilometers.
He also said Ukraine needs investment in military production, especially to make long-range missiles, drones, grenades and artillery rounds.

recommandationVideos.Title: Did China Crack the F-35's Stealth Code? Implications for Air Warfare
recommandationVideos.Description:
Did China Crack the F-35's Stealth Code? Implications for Air Warfare

ðŸ›©ï¸ Greetings, fellow aviation enthusiasts! Today, we delve into a sensitive topic: the alleged compromise of the F-35's vaunted stealth technology. A leaked document has ignited anxieties, raising crucial questions about the future of air warfare. So, strap yourselves in as we dissect the intel and explore the potential ramifications.

A Legacy of Lethal Secrets
Weapons technology thrives on secrecy, and the F-35 embodies this principle like no other aircraft. Its stealth capabilities, akin to an air-borne invisibility cloak, have been a cornerstone of American air dominance for years. From evading radars to striking unseen, the F-35 has redefined aerial combat.

But whispers of China's interest in this forbidden fruit have swirled for years. Suspicious espionage cases and the emergence of China's J-20, bearing an uncanny resemblance to the F-35, only fueled the speculation.

The Leaked Pandora's Box
Now, a leaked document has thrown open the doors to this classified cockpit. Imagine finding the blueprints to Fort Knox casually delivered to your doorstep! This document reportedly contains detailed information on the F-35's radar signature, material composition, and potentially, even deeper secrets.

Is the F-35 Toast? Not So Fast.
Before we sound the alarm bells, let's remember that stealth is a multi-layered onion. While China might have peeled back a few outer layers, the core â€“ the truly classified and most effective technology â€“ likely remains under impregnable lock and key. Replicating such advanced stealth capabilities demands not just the knowledge, but also the precise manufacturing techniques and exotic materials, areas where China is still playing catch-up.

However, a Compromised Onion Still Bites
Even a partially compromised stealth system can pose serious threats. This leak could grant China the ability to detect and target F-35s at significantly longer ranges, a game-changer in aerial combat. The US will need to adapt its tactics and rethink its reliance on this once-impenetrable shield.

The Murky Future of Air Warfare
The landscape of air warfare has just shifted dramatically. Will the F-35 evolve, regaining its cloak of invisibility? Will China's J-20 finally live up to its "Dragon Lady" moniker, challenging American supremacy in the skies? These are the questions that now haunt the minds of military strategists and fighter pilots alike.

Join the Dogfight of Discussion!
This is a complex and evolving situation, and Aviation Future is your platform to stay informed and engaged. Share your thoughts, theories, and questions in the comments below. Let's dissect this dogfight of a situation together and keep the skies of curiosity lit!

Remember, knowledge is power, and in the ever-evolving arena of aviation, staying informed is crucial. So, hit that subscribe button, smash that notification bell, and join us on this thrilling journey through the skies of tomorrow!

Until next time, fly safe! âœˆï¸ðŸš€

recommandationVideos.Title: Ukraine calls for investigation after deadly plane crash in Russia | BBC News
recommandationVideos.Description:
Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky has accused Moscow of "playing with the lives of Ukrainian prisoners", after a deadly plane crash in western Russia.
 
He demanded an international inquiry after Wednesday's crash in the Belgorod region near Ukraine's border.
 
Russia said there were no survivors after Kyiv had downed the Il-76 plane with 65 Ukrainian prisoners of war, six Russian crew and three escorts.
 
Moscow claimed the Ukrainians were being flown for a prisoner exchange.
 
Ukraine's military intelligence (GUR) said it had not been told to ensure safe airspace, as on previous occasions.

recommandationVideos.Title: Ukraine 'blows up Russian Black Sea oil terminal'
recommandationVideos.Description:
A Russian oil terminal on the Black Sea has been blown up in an apparent Ukrainian drone strike.

Video footage from the scene showed a drone flying towards the Tuapse oil depot in Russiaâ€™s Krasnodar region on Wednesday night.

City mayor Sergey Boyko said there were no casualties and the fire was extinguished at 4.53am local time (1.53am GMT).

The prominent Baza Telegram channel said explosions were heard in the city before the fire started at the Rosneft depot as anti-air defences attempted to engage the drone.

Ukraine is yet to officially claim responsibility.

It has attacked four other oil depots in Russia this month, including one in St Petersburg more than 700 miles from Ukraineâ€™s northern border.

recommandationVideos.Title: Eugene Kenneth Smith: First person executed with nitrogen gas took 22 minutes to die
recommandationVideos.Description:
An Alabama prisoner who became the first person to ever be executed using nitrogen gas took 22 minutes to die despite the state promising his death would be quick and painless.

Kenneth Smith shook and writhed for two minutes on Thursday night as his mask filled up with the gas, witnesses said.

The convicted killer is said to have remained conscious, breathing heavily and gasping for a further eight minutes as his sons and crying wife watched on.

Smith, 58, was not pronounced dead until 8.25pm, 22 minutes after the gas was first administered.

But Steve Marshall, Alabamaâ€™s attorney general, insisted that the execution had â€œprovedâ€ nitrogen gas was â€œan effective and humane method of executionâ€.

Read more here: https://www.telegraph.co.uk/us/news/2024/01/26/alabama-executes-murderer-kenneth-smith-nitrogen-gas/

recommandationVideos.Title: What To Do With All The Empty Offices In U.S. Cities | CNBC Marathon
recommandationVideos.Description:
Now that the remote and hybrid work revolution has begun, many cities are filled with empty or half empty offices, creating very quiet downtowns. At the same time, the U.S. is experiencing a housing crisis. CNBC Marathon explores if U.S. cities will convert offices into apartments.

Some U.S. mayors are loosening up rules that determine how developers convert office buildings into apartment complexes. The conversion trend sped up in the 2020s, as the pandemic remote work boom reshaped cities. Declines in office activity are straining tax revenues for city services like education and transit, leading some local leaders to prioritize increased conversion of dated buildings. These rule changes may create some additional housing supply in regions like the U.S. east coast.

Meanwhile, San Francisco is facing its highest office vacancy rates in nearly 30 years. At the same time, the city is facing a housing crisis with the state demanding 82,000 new units of housing to be built by 2031. CNBC sits down with San Francisco Mayor London Breed to discuss how the city could tackle two of its biggest issues head-on. Plus, CNBC visits a building in the Civic Center neighborhood that undertook the biggest office-to-residential conversion in the city to date.

Major American cities such as New York and San Francisco face serious problems â€” mass migration, empty offices and declining tax revenues. These trends have had a direct impact on cities, which rely on tax revenues for funding, a significant portion from commercial real estate. Stijn Van Nieuwerburgh has defined this cycle of spillover effects as the â€˜urban doom loop.â€™

recommandationVideos.Title: How Scharnhorst was Sunk: Battle of the North Cape 1943
recommandationVideos.Description:
In December 1943, in the darkest years of the Second World War at Christmas time, one of the Kriegsmarine's few lethal remaining surface warships was sent on the hunt to win a propaganda victory for the German war effort. Arctic convoy JW55B was headed for Murmansk but was being stalked by Scharnhorst, 5 destroyers and 6 U-Boats. The Germans closed in for the kill - but they didn't know they were steaming straight into a trap. Admiral Bruce Fraser had brought the might of the British Royal Navy to bear including the guns of his flagship HMS Duke of York. Together with the cruiser HMS Belfast, Norfolk, Jamaica and others the German warship would be engaged and destroyed after years of wreaking havoc in the Atlantic. This is the remarkable true story of the battleship Scharnhorst, her sister Gneisenau and the remarkable events that led to the legendary ship's sinking.

Please note: this film is not intended to glorify the Third Reich nor any of its genocidal political motivations but rather to serve as a tribute to the sailors of all nationalities who lost their lives at sea in those dark years 1939-1945. All imagery and material used in this film is within a purely historical and immersive context.

This film was written by Joseph Lavender and edited by Michael Brady.
Animated by Jack Gibson.
3D models by Thomas Beerens via Sketchfab.
Music via Epidemic Sound.
Archival footage including original German propoganda films digitised by 3dhistory.de: https://3dhistory.de/wordpress/historical-film-footage/

2024 has begun a new phase of the war between Russia and Ukraine, and this time it is all about information. Today's video is about the manipulation of that information space in the context of lines on maps theory. Information wars presuppose that there is some underlying truth about the world, and each side is trying to convince the other that its own perception is correct and the rival's is wrong. We will cover how Ukraine's 2023 offensive fits into this and the long list of unsolved mysteries that are keeping the information war clouded.

Check out my new book "How Ukraine Survived": https://amzn.to/47gnlEf. You can also read it for free by signing up for a Kindle Unlimited trial at https://amzn.to/3QMsBr8. (I use affiliate links, meaning I earn a commission when you make a transaction through them. Even if you read for free, you are still supporting the channel.)

Not long ago, the Russian arms export industry was prestigious and profitable. Now, deep into the war with Ukraine, it is facing substantial challenges. This video examines how the arms export industry works, both economically and politically. It then connects the actions of the invasion to the pain points Russia is currently facing. We also explore how two competitors in the industry---the United States and China---are trying to take advantage of the situation.

recommandationVideos.Title: How Scharnhorst was Sunk: Battle of the North Cape 1943
recommandationVideos.Description:
In December 1943, in the darkest years of the Second World War at Christmas time, one of the Kriegsmarine's few lethal remaining surface warships was sent on the hunt to win a propaganda victory for the German war effort. Arctic convoy JW55B was headed for Murmansk but was being stalked by Scharnhorst, 5 destroyers and 6 U-Boats. The Germans closed in for the kill - but they didn't know they were steaming straight into a trap. Admiral Bruce Fraser had brought the might of the British Royal Navy to bear including the guns of his flagship HMS Duke of York. Together with the cruiser HMS Belfast, Norfolk, Jamaica and others the German warship would be engaged and destroyed after years of wreaking havoc in the Atlantic. This is the remarkable true story of the battleship Scharnhorst, her sister Gneisenau and the remarkable events that led to the legendary ship's sinking.

Please note: this film is not intended to glorify the Third Reich nor any of its genocidal political motivations but rather to serve as a tribute to the sailors of all nationalities who lost their lives at sea in those dark years 1939-1945. All imagery and material used in this film is within a purely historical and immersive context.

This film was written by Joseph Lavender and edited by Michael Brady.
Animated by Jack Gibson.
3D models by Thomas Beerens via Sketchfab.
Music via Epidemic Sound.
Archival footage including original German propoganda films digitised by 3dhistory.de: https://3dhistory.de/wordpress/historical-film-footage/

Oceanliner Designs explores the design, construction, engineering and operation of historyâ€™s greatest vesselsâ€“ from Titanic to Queen Mary and from the Empress of Ireland to the Lusitania. Join maritime researcher and illustrator Michael Brady as he tells the stories behind some of history's most famous ocean liners and machines!

recommandationVideos.Description:
Two hero Ukrainian soldiers saved their wounded comrades by carrying them on their shoulders across the battlefields of Bakhmut. Maliy, a platoon commander with the 93rd Brigade, and Ahmed, one of his men, rode into action after two of their brothers-in-arms were hurt defending the village of Klishchiivka, to the south of Bakhmut. Video shows how they found the men, both with leg injuries, lying on the battlefield after being torn up by Russian artillery. They drag one on a stretcher and carry another on their backs to escape. But halfway off the battlefield they are forced to abandon the stretcher as both men are carried out of danger and to the hospital.

recommandationVideos.Title: Ukraine brigades target Russian soldiers in Avdiivka as enemy troops use drones to deliver weapons
recommandationVideos.Description:
Ukraineâ€™s 47th Brigade is locked in fierce combat with Russia in the town of Avdiivka. First-person footage from an assault squad shows them charging a Russian position using grenades and rifles to drive out Putinâ€™s soldiers and take over their foxholes. They even manage to capture a Russian soldier who was wounded in the fighting. But the Russians hit back, using their own squads to blast Ukrainian outposts and attack a trench system, with the fire-fight captured from above by a drone.
The drone even delivers weapons to a soldier in the middle of the battle. Soldiers of the 47th were also involved in a firefight which saw a Russian T-90 tank destroyed by two Bradley IFVs using nothing but their chain-guns. Brave drivers and gunners managed to cripple the tank, which Russia brags is one of its most modern and best-protected, though the crew escaped. Afterwards, the gunner of one of the Bradleyâ€™s said he knew where the tank's weak spots were thanks to online video games. #ukraine #russia #dailymail

recommandationVideos.Title: Russian oil refinery burns after Ukrainian drone strike as factories are torched
recommandationVideos.Description:
A massive oil refinery in Russia burst into flames after being struck by a long-range Ukrainian drone, in the latest attack of its kind. The Tuapse refinery, located around 250 miles from the frontline, burned for several hours before the fire could be extinguished. More footage showed what appeared to be a drone heading for the refinery, after apparently being launched from Ukraine. Meanwhile three factories, two of them located more than 2,000 miles from Ukraine, were also set on fire, which has also become a common occurrence. Tuapse produces about 240,000 barrels of oil per day and is mainly used to supply Turkey, China, and Singapore.

recommandationVideos.Title: Ukraine calls for investigation after deadly plane crash in Russia | BBC News
recommandationVideos.Description:
Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky has accused Moscow of "playing with the lives of Ukrainian prisoners", after a deadly plane crash in western Russia.
 
He demanded an international inquiry after Wednesday's crash in the Belgorod region near Ukraine's border.
 
Russia said there were no survivors after Kyiv had downed the Il-76 plane with 65 Ukrainian prisoners of war, six Russian crew and three escorts.
 
Moscow claimed the Ukrainians were being flown for a prisoner exchange.
 
Ukraine's military intelligence (GUR) said it had not been told to ensure safe airspace, as on previous occasions.

recommandationVideos.Title: The fighter that wrecked the Spitfire
recommandationVideos.Description:
If you mentioned BMW to most people, they think of a car. They don't think of something with an engine of 1,800 horsepower powering one of the deadliest fighters of the Second World War. The Focke-Wulf 190.

Kurt Tank's design of the Focke-Wulf 190 was hunched like a pitbull. Very strong in design. Tapered wing edges. It could roll very fast. It could take a lot of punishment. And the performance was electrifying.

In this video, IWM Duxford's Graham Rodgers explored the history of Germany's 'Butcher Bird'.

recommandationVideos.Title: Inside Rural Russia: When Military and Patriotism Are Your Life | ENDEVR Documentary
recommandationVideos.Description:
Inside Rural Russia: When Military and Patriotism Are Your Life | Town of Glory | ENDEVR Documentary

Watch 'The Oligarch's Wife - Married to a Hunted Russian Billionaire' here: https://youtu.be/QCJpX2nhY3Q

A heroic Soviet past and a destitute post-industrial present make the provincial town of Yenya susceptible to the Kremlin's aggressive anti-Western propaganda leading to the militarization of society from kindergarten to pension age. With few exceptions, Yelnyans raise their children to become good patriots. They donâ€™t mind the eerie, all-encompassing militarization of society.

Filmed over the course of three years, this film introduces Western viewers to the small and prototypical provincial Russian town of Yelnya where people admire Vladimir Putin for making Russia great again. Yelnya has remained economically marginalized ever since the Soviet Union collapsed. But people have regained pride. They believe that President Putin is bringing back glory and power to the Russian nation. Not many object to the constant propaganda claims that fascism is threatening once again from the US and Europe and that Russia must stand ready to defend itself.

recommandationVideos.Title: Ukrainian soldiers storm Russian-held 'Cyclops' trench in terrifying assault footage near Bakhmut
recommandationVideos.Description:
Ukrainian soldiers storm Russian-held 'Cyclops' trench in terrifying assault footage near Bakhmut: The K2 Battalion ( https://youtube.com/@k2_bat ) of the 54th Mechanised Brigade  posted this video of their infantry assault on a Russian trench called 'Cyclops' near the city of Bakhmut. An earlier part of the video shows Russian troops being bombarded by artillery. In this video posted in April Ukrainian drone pilots drop bombs on the trench before infantry launch an assault. The fighting is believed to have taken place earlier this year, before Ukrainian forces lost much of the city.

recommandationVideos.Title: Ukraine devastate a Russian armoured attack on the town of Kupyansk
recommandationVideos.Description:
Ukraine devastated a Russian armoured attack on the town of Kupyansk, amid heavy fighting between the two sides in western Luhansk oblast. Video shows two Russian tanks and two armoured vehicles attacking the Ukrainians, past the destroyed remains of several earlier attacks. But this one fares no better, as the column is hit by mines, suicide drones, and anti-tank missiles, turning it into a smouldering wreck. Russian troops struck back, using artillery and their own suicide drones to destroy a Ukrainian arms dump, and set a tank alight. But it was only minor damage compared to their failed attack, as a second angle showed the tanks and armoured vehicles exploding under heavy fire.

recommandationVideos.Title: Russian oil refinery burns after Ukrainian drone strike as factories are torched
recommandationVideos.Description:
A massive oil refinery in Russia burst into flames after being struck by a long-range Ukrainian drone, in the latest attack of its kind. The Tuapse refinery, located around 250 miles from the frontline, burned for several hours before the fire could be extinguished. More footage showed what appeared to be a drone heading for the refinery, after apparently being launched from Ukraine. Meanwhile three factories, two of them located more than 2,000 miles from Ukraine, were also set on fire, which has also become a common occurrence. Tuapse produces about 240,000 barrels of oil per day and is mainly used to supply Turkey, China, and Singapore.
